                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>\n                <placeName>Charleston</placeName>\n                <date>August 10<hi rend=\"sup\">th</hi> 1852</date>\n            </p>\n            <p>\n                <addressee>Rev. I. Leeser</addressee>\n                <placeName>Phil</placeName>\n            </p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">My dear Sir</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(2)\">Your esteemed favor is at hand, also<lb/> the <date>August</date>\n                number of the Occident; I trust the general<lb/> contents may cause men to see the\n                necessity of making<lb/> some improvements in our Synagogue\n                <sic>goverment</sic>.</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">Since I last wrote you, <persName>Rev S Jacobs</persName> has\n                been<lb/> here and he will in all probability be the minister<lb/> of KKSI. as over\n                Thirty members including <persName>M Levin</persName><lb/> and <persName>M\n                    Valentine</persName> have pledged themselves to vote for him.<lb/> To the great\n                injustice of any other candidate who may<lb/> be on the way to apply for the\n                situation. I begin<lb/> to see now that those gentlemen who made objections<lb/> to\n                your being our minister on account of your personal<lb/> inconvenience<add>?</add>,\n                know more about the vacillating character<lb/> of the Congregation, and had <hi\n                    rend=\"underline\">your interest</hi> more at heart<lb/> that <hi rend=\"underline\"\n                    >I</hi> gave them credit for. They pledged themselves<lb/> to you, and\n                notwithstanding your declining to become<lb/> a candidate, if they really wanted you\n                they should<lb/> at the Election have voted for you at all events for<lb/> the first\n                ballots the converse was the case on receipt of your<lb/> letter they no longer\n                considered themselves bound, and almost<lb/> immediately, transferred their\n                preference for <persName>Dr Eckman</persName><lb/> a number sufficient to elect him,\n                was obtained<lb/> (not by me for I took no ostensible part in it.)<lb/>\n                <persName>M Valentine</persName> intended to call a caucus meeting to<lb/> get those\n                persons to pledge themselves to elect him</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p35h7cd9n/canvas/p1"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
